<p class="eyebrow">Getting started</p>
<h1 class="mt-2 font-display text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Self-host with Docker.</h1>
<p class="mt-3 text-muted-foreground">Authly ships as a prebuilt image on Docker Hub. <strong>No source checkout, no build, no cloud account, no licence key, no phone-home</strong> — download one Compose file, run it, done. Your data never leaves your database.</p>

<div class="mt-4 card card-body !py-3 flex items-start gap-3 border-l-4 border-l-primary text-sm">
    <i data-lucide="hand-helping" class="size-4 text-primary mt-0.5 shrink-0"></i>
    <div>Prefer the step-by-step page with OS-specific Docker install tabs? See <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/self-host">the Self-Host guide</a>. This page is the condensed reference.</div>
</div>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Prerequisites</h2>
<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Only <strong>Docker</strong> (Engine 24+ or Docker Desktop). PostgreSQL 16, Redis 7 and the observability stack all ship inside the Compose file.</p>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Quick start (no GitHub needed)</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
    <li>Create an empty folder and download the Compose file into it:
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/download/docker-compose"><i data-lucide="download" class="inline size-3.5"></i> docker-compose.yml</a>
        (optional: <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/download/env-example">.env.example</a>).</li>
    <li>From that folder, run:</li>
</ol>
<div class="mt-3 code-surface px-4 py-3 text-sm"><code>docker compose up -d
docker compose logs -f app        <span class="tok-com"># watch migrations apply</span></code></div>
<p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted-foreground">The image is pulled straight from Docker Hub (<code class="text-primary">@Authly.Web.SiteInfo.DockerImage</code>). Open <code class="text-primary">http://localhost:8080</code> and click <strong>Sign up</strong> to create your first workspace — that account becomes its administrator. EF Core migrations apply automatically on first boot.</p>

<details class="mt-3 text-sm">
    <summary class="cursor-pointer text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground">Pull the image manually instead</summary>
    <div class="mt-2 code-surface px-4 py-3"><code>docker pull @(Authly.Web.SiteInfo.DockerImage):latest</code></div>
</details>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Environment variables</h2>
<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">Set these in a <code>.env</code> file next to <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. Everything has a dev-safe default, so the stack runs with no <code>.env</code> at all — but set your own <code>ENCRYPTION_KEY</code> and DB password for anything real.</p>
<div class="card overflow-hidden">
    <div class="overflow-x-auto scroll-thin">
        <table class="table">
            <thead><tr><th>Variable</th><th>Required</th><th>What it is</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td><code>ENCRYPTION_KEY</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-danger">Required</span></td><td>32-byte base64 key (AES-256-GCM). Generate: <code>openssl rand -base64 32</code>.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>POSTGRES_PASSWORD</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-neutral">Default</span></td><td>Bundled Postgres password — override in production.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>APP_PORT</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-neutral">Default</span></td><td>Host port for the app (default 8080).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>DATABASE_URL</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-neutral">Default</span></td><td>Postgres connection string (bundled service by default).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>REDIS_URL</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-neutral">Default</span></td><td>Redis host:port (bundled service by default).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>RETENTION_AUDIT_DAYS</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-info">Optional</span></td><td>Audit-log retention (default 365).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>RETENTION_LOGIN_HISTORY_DAYS</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-info">Optional</span></td><td>Login-history retention (default 90).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-info">Optional</span></td><td>OpenTelemetry collector endpoint (bundled collector by default).</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
</div>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Updating</h2>
<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Pull the latest image and recreate the app container — your data persists in the <code>pgdata</code> volume:</p>
<div class="mt-3 code-surface px-4 py-3 text-sm"><code>docker compose pull
docker compose up -d</code></div>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Observability (built in)</h2>
<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">The Compose file already bundles Grafana, Prometheus, Loki, Tempo and an OpenTelemetry Collector — they start with <code>docker compose up -d</code>. Grafana is at <code class="text-primary">http://localhost:3000</code> (Prometheus :9090 · Loki :3100 · OTLP :4317/4318).</p>
<p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted-foreground">Exporting is opt-in: nothing leaves the app until you turn it on. With the bundled stack, the app is already pointed at the collector via <code>OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT</code>. To send telemetry to your own backend (Grafana Cloud, Honeycomb, Datadog, Azure Monitor…), configure it in the admin panel.</p>

<h3 class="font-display text-base font-bold mt-6 mb-2">Set the exporter path in the admin panel</h3>
<ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
    <li>Sign in to the admin console and open <strong>Observability</strong> (<code class="text-primary">/tenantadmin/observability</code>). Requires the <code>observability.manage</code> permission.</li>
    <li>Toggle <strong>Enabled</strong> on.</li>
    <li>Fill in the fields below, <strong>Save</strong>, then restart the app for changes to take effect: <code>docker compose restart app</code>.</li>
</ol>
<div class="mt-4 card overflow-hidden">
    <div class="overflow-x-auto scroll-thin">
        <table class="table">
            <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>What to enter</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td><strong>Exporter</strong></td><td><code>OTLP</code> (any OpenTelemetry backend) or <code>Azure Monitor</code>.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>OTLP endpoint</strong></td><td>Where to send telemetry. For the <em>bundled</em> collector use <code>http://otel-collector:4317</code> (the app reaches it by service name on the Compose network). For an external backend, paste its OTLP URL, e.g. <code>https://otlp-gateway.grafana.net/otlp</code>.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>OTLP headers</strong></td><td>Optional auth headers for the backend, comma-separated <code>key=value</code> — e.g. <code>Authorization=Basic &lt;token&gt;</code>. Stored encrypted; leave blank to keep the existing value.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Azure Monitor connection string</strong></td><td>Only when Exporter = Azure Monitor. Stored encrypted.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Signals</strong></td><td>Toggle <code>traces</code> / <code>metrics</code> / <code>logs</code> independently.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Trace sampling ratio</strong></td><td>0.0–1.0 (1.0 = sample everything).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Audit log-stream endpoint / key</strong></td><td>Optional — stream the audit log to an external SIEM/webhook. The key is stored encrypted.</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="mt-4 card card-body !py-3 flex items-start gap-3 border-l-4 border-l-primary text-sm">
    <i data-lucide="info" class="size-4 text-primary mt-0.5 shrink-0"></i>
    <div>The admin-panel config <strong>overrides</strong> the <code>OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT</code> env var once <em>Enabled</em> is on. The env var is just the startup fallback used when no enabled config row exists. Either way, exporter changes apply only after an app restart.</div>
</div>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Stop &amp; clean up</h2>
<div class="code-surface px-4 py-3 text-sm"><code>docker compose down            <span class="tok-com"># keep data</span>
docker compose down -v         <span class="tok-com"># wipe the pgdata volume</span></code></div>

<h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-2">Build from source (optional)</h2>
<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Want to build the image yourself instead of pulling it? Clone the repo — it ships the <code>Dockerfile</code> and a build-based <code>docker-compose.yml</code>:</p>
<div class="mt-3 code-surface px-4 py-3 text-sm"><code>git clone @(Authly.Web.SiteInfo.GitHubUrl).git
cd authly
docker compose up --build -d</code></div>

